Main Terraform Commands we Use Daily:-
1: terraform init ---> To initilize the terraform in that folder
4: terraform destroy -----> Destroy the created resources.
How to Write Terraform Provider File:-
Step 1: We start with writing terraform block
This is terrafrom block, inside this block we write our infrastructure code to create resources.
Step 2: Now we write required_providers Block.
This is required provider block, in this we mention the cloud provider details, we can also use multi-cloud here, means
we can specify two cloud providers.
Step 3: Now specify the resource block.
This is the only main and unique block, like this is were the actual cloud provider details are written, and using this block
we can say which cloud provider we are using.
like in our case we are using AWS, so we have specified the name of the instance and ip address starting.
What are Input.tf and Output.tf Files??
- Input.tf files are files, environment variables file, in this files we can specify the
important data and resources that we want to hide.
- It is also used for changing the Terraform provider file, in future, suppose tomarrow we want
to migrate from AWS to Azure, so we can just modify the inputs.tf file.
- Seggregate the variables from main provider file to inputs.tf file.
- Outputs.tf file are files that outputs the result that terraform creates.
- example if an ec2 instance is created, output the private and public IP address of that created machine.
- in outputs.tf we mention this things, so that terraform will understand this.
- This file is very important, terraform doesnt know anything about the created instances or resources.
- As we studied earlier Terraform also supports Tracking of infrastructure.
- So to maintain the state, information of created resources terraform creates a file called "terraform.tfstate".
- It keeps track of the every resource it creates.
- Only one file is created for one Terraform providers file
- This state file cannot be uploaded to github or remotly, because it has lot off sensitive information.
- Never store state files on local machine.
- Always store state files in an remote backend. eg: s3 bucket or etc.
Ideal Setup for Terraform in Oraganization
- The situation here is, suppose a developer wants to create an EC2 instance, but the manager have only given
AWS resource creation access to DevOps engg.
- So now we have to write terraform script that allows developers to create EC2 instances, So we write an CI/CD
pipeline that creates an EC2 Instance.
- So the developer will execute the pipeline using github, and this will create the AWS resource.
- But now since we are using remote backend to store our State files, i.e S3 Bucket.
- So all records will be centralized and only single tfState file will be created.
- So now suppose 10 developers at a time runs this CI/CD pipeline then also terraform will ony allow specific users at a time.
- so for every user, the same state file is used and modified.
- This are just reusable code written by you or someone else, that you can use
- If any job or any task which is same or repeating then we can create a module,
so that we can use same block of script again withut writing it again for the same task.
